# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: adams-county-colorado
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:adams-county-colorado/1904-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] The **1904 United States presidential election in Colorado** took place on November 8, 1904.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1904-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] All contemporary 45 states were part of the 1904 United States presidential election.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1904-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] State voters chose five electors to the Electoral College, which selected the president and vice president.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1904-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Colorado was won by the Republican nominees, incumbent President Theodore Roosevelt of New York and his running mate Charles W.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1904-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] They defeated the Democratic nominees, former Chief Judge of New York Court of Appeals Alton B.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1904-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Parker and his running mate, former US Senator Henry G.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1904-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Roosevelt won the state by a margin of 14.18%.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1904-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Roosevelt's victory in Colorado was part of a national landslide.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1904-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] He was the only Republican candidate to win the state between 1888 and 1920.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1908-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] The **1908 United States presidential election in Colorado** took place on November 3, 1908, as part of the 1908 United States presidential election.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1908-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Voters chose five representatives, or electors, to the Electoral College, who voted for president and vice president.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1908-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] The 1908 Democratic National Convention was held in Denver between July 7 and 10.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1908-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Colorado was won by the Democratic nominee, former U.S.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1908-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Representative William Jennings Bryan and his running mate John W.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1908-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] They defeated the Republican nominee, Secretary of War William Howard Taft and his running mate James S.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1908-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Bryan won the state by a narrow margin of 1.12%.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1908-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Bryan had previously won Colorado against William McKinley in both 1896 and 1900.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1908-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Until 2016, this was the last presidential election where a Democrat carried Colorado without winning the presidency, and was the last time until 2024 that the state had backed a Democrat who lost the popular vote.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1910-united-states-census] The **1910 United States census**, conducted by the Census Bureau on April 15, 1910, determined the resident population of the United States to be 92,228,496, an increase of 21 percent over the 76,212,168 persons enumerated during the 1900 census.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1910-united-states-census] The 1910 census switched from a portrait page orientation to a landscape orientation.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1910-united-states-census] This was the last census in which Texas did not record any top 50 largest cities by population, despite being the 5th most populous state at the time.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1910-united-states-census] It was also the first census in which all the top 50 largest cities had population over 100,000.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1910-united-states-census] The 1910 census was the first to use metropolitan districts, the predecessor to modern metropolitan statistical areas, which were defined for all cities with at least 200,000 people.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1910-united-states-census] Edward Dana Durand, then-head of the Bureau of Corporations, was appointed in 1909 to oversee the census. $14 million were allocated to conduct the census.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1910-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1910 census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1910-united-states-census] Number of dwelling house in order of visitation.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1910-united-states-census] Number of family in order of visitation.
