[src:adams-county-colorado/1910-united-states-census] The original census enumeration sheets were microfilmed by the Census Bureau in the 1940s; after which the original sheets were destroyed.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1910-united-states-census] The microfilmed census is available in rolls from the National Archives and Records Administration.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1910-united-states-census] Several organizations also host images of the microfilmed census online, along with digital indices.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1910-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1910 census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1910-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with electronic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1912-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] The **1912 United States presidential election in Colorado** took place on November 5, 1912, as part of the 1912 United States presidential election.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1912-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] State voters chose six representatives, or electors, to the Electoral College, who voted for president and vice president.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1912-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Colorado was won by New Jersey Governor Woodrow Wilson (D–New Jersey), running with governor of Indiana Thomas R.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1912-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Debs (S–Indiana), running with the first Socialist mayor of a major city in the United States Emil Seidel, with 6.15% of the popular vote.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1916-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] The **1916 United States presidential election in Colorado** took place on November 7, 1916.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1916-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] All contemporary forty-eight states were part of the 1916 United States presidential election.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1916-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] State voters chose six electors to the Electoral College, who voted for president and vice president.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1916-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] These factors combined to give Wilson a powerful victory over Republican nominee Charles Evans Hughes.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1916-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Wilson won by 25.99 percentage points and carried every county except Sedgwick (albeit losing by ten votes), the furthest northeast, which had also been one of two counties to back Roosevelt four years earlier.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1916-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] This is the second-best Democratic margin in Colorado presidential election history behind Bryan's five-to-one win in the “free silver” 1896 election, although Lyndon B.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1916-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Johnson would exceed Wilson's vote share in 1964.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1920-united-states-census] The **1920 United States census**, conducted by the Census Bureau during one month from January 5, 1920, determined the resident population of the United States to be 106,021,537, an increase of 15.0 percent over the 92,228,496 persons enumerated during the 1910 census.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1920-united-states-census] The 1920 Census was determined for 1 January 1920.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1920-united-states-census] The actual date of the enumeration appears on the heading of each page of the census schedule, but all responses were to reflect the individual's status as of 1 January, even if the status had changed between 1 January and the day of enumeration.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1920-united-states-census] In 1929, Congress passed the Reapportionment Act of 1929 which provided for a permanent method of reapportionment and fixed the number of representatives at 435.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1920-united-states-census] This was the first census in which the United States recorded a population of more than 100 million.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1920-united-states-census] It was also the first census in which a state—New York—recorded a population of more than ten million.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1920-united-states-census] This census also marked a significant population shift from rural to urban.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1920-united-states-census] According to the Census Bureau, "Beginning in 1910, the minimum population threshold to be categorized as an urban place was set at 2,500.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1920-united-states-census] 'Urban' was defined as including all territory, persons, and housing units within an incorporated area that met the population threshold.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1920-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1920 census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1920-united-states-census] Location of 50 largest cities by population in the United States in 1920.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1920-united-states-census] The original census enumeration sheets were microfilmed by the Census Bureau in the 1940s, after which the original sheets were destroyed.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1920-united-states-census] Several organizations also host images of the microfilmed census online, and digital indices.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1920-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1920 census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1920-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] The **1920 United States presidential election in Colorado** was held on November 2, 1920, as part of the 1920 United States presidential election.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1920-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Political unrest seen in the Palmer Raids and the "Red Scare" further added to the unpopularity of the Democratic Party, since this global political turmoil produced considerable fear of alien revolutionaries invading the country.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1920-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Demand in the West for exclusion of Asian immigrants became even stronger than it had been before.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1920-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] All these factors combined to produce a national landslide, with a swing of almost twenty-nine percentage points to the Republicans vis-à-vis of four years earlier.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1920-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Colorado mirrored this trend, with a total swing of 49.38 points from Wilson's 26-point 1916 victory where he carried every county except Sedgwick.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1920-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] This time, Harding would not merely become only the second Republican victor in the state since James B.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1920-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Weaver’s Populist victory transitioned the state into a Democratic-leaning one, but become the only presidential candidate in history to carry all Colorado’s counties.
[src:adams-county-colorado/1920-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] The state was still 2.84 points more Democratic than the nation at-large despite Harding’s historic county sweep.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] On May 30, 1854, the Kansas–Nebraska Act created the Territory of Nebraska and Territory of Kansas, divided by the Parallel 40° North (168th Avenue in present-day Adams County).
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] The future Adams County, Colorado, occupied a strip of northern Arapahoe County, Kansas Territory, immediately south of the Nebraska Territory.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] "Colonel Jack" Henderson built a ranch, trading post, and hotel on Henderson Island in the South Platte River in Arapahoe County, Kansas Territory.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] Jack Henderson was the former editor and proprietor of the Leavenworth (Kansas Territory) Journal and an outspoken pro-slavery politician who had been accused of vote fraud in eastern Kansas.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] Henderson sold meat and provisions to gold seekers on their way up the South Platte River Trail to the gold fields during the Pike's Peak Gold Rush.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] Henderson Island was the first permanent settlement in the South Platte River Valley between Fort Saint Vrain in the Nebraska Territory and the Cherry Creek Diggings in the Kansas Territory.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] Jack Henderson eventually returned to eastern Kansas and fought for the Union in the American Civil War.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] Henderson Island is today the site of the Riverdale Regional Park, formerly known as the Adams County Regional Park and Fairgrounds.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] The eastern portion of the Kansas Territory was admitted to the Union as the State of Kansas on January 29, 1861, and on February 28, 1861, the remaining western portion of the territory was made part of the new Colorado Territory.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] The Colorado Territory created Arapahoe County, on November 1, 1861, and Colorado was admitted to the Union on August 1, 1876.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] In 1901, the Colorado General Assembly voted to split Arapahoe County into three parts: a new Adams County, a new consolidated City and County of Denver, and the remainder of the Arapahoe County to be renamed South Arapahoe County.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] A ruling by the Colorado Supreme Court, subsequent legislation, and a referendum delayed the creation of Adams County until November 15, 1902.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] Governor James Bradley Orman designated Brighton as the temporary Adams County Seat.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] Adams County originally stretched 160 miles (260 kilometers) from present-day Sheridan Boulevard to the Kansas state border.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] On May 12, 1903, the eastern 88 miles (142 kilometers)-wide section of Adams County was transferred to the new Washington County and the new Yuma County, reducing the length of Adams County to the present 72 miles (116 kilometers) and its area to the present 1,184 square miles (3,070 km2).
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] On November 8, 1904, Adams County voters chose Brighton as the permanent county seat.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] A 1989 vote transferred 53 square miles (140 square kilometers) of Adams County to the City and County of Denver for the proposed Denver International Airport, leaving the densely populated western portion of the county as two oddly-shaped peninsulas.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] Adams County lost the tip of its northwest corner when the consolidated City and County of Broomfield was created on November 15, 2001.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] Census Bureau, the county has a total area of 1,184 square miles (3,070 km2), of which 1,168 square miles (3,030 km2) is land and 16 square miles (41 km2) (1.4%) is water.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] Adams County surrounds (and surrendered the land for) most of Denver International Airport which are in the City and County of Denver.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] As of the 2020 census, the county had a population of 519,572.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] Of the residents, 25.7% were under the age of 18 and 11.1% were 65 years of age or older; the median age was 34.4 years.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] For every 100 females there were 101.9 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 100.9 males.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] 96.0% of residents lived in urban areas and 4.0% lived in rural areas.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] The racial makeup of the county was 55.8% White, 3.4% Black or African American, 1.8% American Indian and Alaska Native, 4.5% Asian, 0.2% Native Hawaiian and Pacific Islander, 16.8% from some other race, and 17.6% from two or more races.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] Hispanic or Latino residents of any race comprised 41.7% of the population.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] There were 178,525 households in the county, of which 38.1% had children under the age of 18 living with them and 23.6% had a female householder with no spouse or partner present.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] About 20.9% of all households were made up of individuals and 7.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] There were 186,544 housing units, of which 4.3% were vacant.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] Among occupied housing units, 66.5% were owner-occupied and 33.5% were renter-occupied.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.0% and the rental vacancy rate was 6.9%.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] As of the 2000 census, there were 363,857 people, 128,156 households, and 92,144 families residing in the county.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] The population density was 305 people per square mile (118 people/km2).
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] There were 132,594 housing units at an average density of 111 per square mile (43/km2).
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] The racial makeup of the county was 77.29% White, 2.97% Black or African American, 1.19% Native American, 3.21% Asian, 0.12% Pacific Islander, 11.73% from other races, and 3.49% from two or more races.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] 28.19% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] There were 128,156 households, out of which 37.80% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 53.80% were married couples living together, 12.10% had a female householder with no husband present, and 28.10% were non-families.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] 21.20% of all households were made up of individuals, and 5.50% had someone who was 65 years of age or older living alone.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] The average household size was 2.81 and the average family size was 3.27.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] In the county, the population was spread out, with 28.60% under the age of 18, 10.30% from 18 to 24, 34.00% from 25 to 44, 19.40% from 45 to 64, and 7.80% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] For every 100 females, there were 102.80 males.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 102.10 males.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] The median income for a household in the county was $47,323, and the median income for a family was $52,517.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] Males had a median income of $36,499 versus $28,053 for females.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] The per capita income for the county was $19,944.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] About 6.50% of families and 8.90% of the population were below the poverty line, including 10.90% of those under age 18 and 7.30% of those age 65 or over.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] In 2000, the largest denominational groups were Catholics (with 60,429 members) and Evangelical Protestants (with 25,552 members).
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] The largest religious bodies were the Catholic Church (with 60,429 adherents) and the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (with 6,808 adherents).
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] Adams County has a Board of Commissioners that operate as a collective governing board.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] There are five members that form the Board of Commissioners with each elected to represent a district or portion of the county.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] There are other elected officials that oversee an aspect or department of county operations.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] Adams County lies within the 17th Judicial District which is represented by District Attorney Brian Mason.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] Adams County is predominately Democratic, not having voted Republican since Ronald Reagan in 1984.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] In 2016, Hillary Clinton won the county without a majority, becoming the first Democrat to do so since her husband Bill Clinton in 1992.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] In the 2020 election, Joe Biden easily won the county with a majority of the vote, a percentage similar to Barack Obama in 2012 and 2008 but with a much larger vote count.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] Despite its Democratic majority, Adams County is significantly less Democratic than most other counties in the Denver metro area, frequently swinging towards the national trend.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] Despite Biden's overwhelming victory in 2020, the county swung hard back towards Trump in 2024, reducing the Democratic margin of victory from nearly 20% to under 10%.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] This came even as Colorado failed to swing as hard as most other states.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] The county is also home to the Westminster campus of Front Range Community College, the largest community college by enrollment in Colorado.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] Up until 1999 when Colorado ceased coding license plates by county, Adams County used the following codes on license plates issued to passenger vehicles: TE-UF, GA-GG, SAA-SEW, and SEY-TZZ.
[src:adams-county-colorado/adams-county-colorado] Adams County was featured as the fictional rival of South Park's peewee hockey team in the *South Park* episode "Stanley's Cup".
